{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17642611","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17642611"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:42:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:42:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17954"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17954","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17954"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.04,0.04,0.88,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10668"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78856"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10668"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17954"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64205"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"7198"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24850"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24853"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78856"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents with progressive unilateral hearing loss and tinnitus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following skull foramina is most likely involved in this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Foramen magnum","Foramen ovale","Hypoglossal canal","Internal acoustic meatus","Jugular foramen"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einternal acoustic meatus\u003C/strong\u003E transmits the vestibulocochlear nerve (CN VIII) and facial nerve (CN VII). Unilateral hearing loss and tinnitus suggest pathology affecting the vestibulocochlear nerve or its surrounding structures as they pass through this canal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options can be excluded:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForamen magnum\u003C/strong\u003E transmits the medulla oblongata, vertebral arteries, and spinal accessory nerve\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForamen ovale\u003C/strong\u003E transmits the mandibular branch of the trigeminal nerve\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypoglossal canal\u003C/strong\u003E transmits the hypoglossal nerve (CN XII) which innervates tongue muscles\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EJugular foramen\u003C/strong\u003E transmits the glossopharyngeal, vagus, and accessory nerves (CN IX, X, XI) plus the internal jugular vein\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon pathologies affecting structures in the internal acoustic meatus include vestibular schwannoma (acoustic neuroma) and inflammatory conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The internal acoustic meatus transmits cranial nerve VII (facial) and VIII (vestibulocochlear) from the brainstem to their peripheral targets.","Symptoms of hearing loss and vertigo typically indicate pathology involving structures passing through the internal acoustic meatus.","The vestibulocochlear nerve carries both auditory and balance information from the inner ear to the brain."],"references":["Singh, V. (2023). Textbook of Anatomy-Head, Neck and Brain, Volume III-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Patestas, M. A., \u0026 Gartner, L. P. (2016). A textbook of neuroanatomy. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Patel, C. R., Fernandez-Miranda, J. C., Wang, W. H., \u0026 Wang, E. W. (2016). Skull Base Anatomy. Otolaryngologic clinics of North America, 49(1), 9\u201320. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.otc.2015.09.001","Anderson, B. W., Kortz, M. W., Black, A. C., \u0026 Al Kharazi, K. A. (2023). Anatomy, Head and Neck, Skull. In StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64205"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17954"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64205","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64205"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T07:09:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T07:11:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10668"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78856"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonym